la pintura es un retrato póstumo de un ancestro, noble princesa inca, comisionado por sus descendientes en los últimos años de la colonia, período en que reclamaba el reconocimiento de la nobleza inca como parte del pasado común de muchos peruanos.
la ñusta se ve acompañada sólo por un esclavo (un enano) que la cubre con un quitasol- a la usanza de los retratos reales españoles- y una pequeña mesa que porta el escudo de la familia.

🏵🏵
.
.
.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text_retweet:
rp @jessyforthevoiceless why the dairy industry is cruel on every level.👇🏼
• 
when a mother cow gives birth, her calf will be removed within 36 hours, so the farmers can steal and sell the milk that is meant for her baby. (organic-, free range-, pasture raised- farm or not.)
• 
cows are pregnant for 9 months, like humans, and there's a natural, strong bond between a mother cow and her calf.
so following their traumatic separation, the mother will bellow and scream for days, wondering where her baby is. 
the answer depends on the gender of the calf. if male, he will probably either be shot and tossed into a bin, or he'll be sold to be raised for veal, which delays his death by just a matter of months. • 
calves who are sold for veal will be stuck inside a small pen or a veal crate so they won't develop any muscle tissue so their 'meat' stays tender.
they stay there until they are transported for slaughter at only 18 - 20 weeks old.
• 
if the calf is female, she will usually be prepared for her own entry into dairy production, where she will face the same cycle of terror that her mother is trapped in: forced impregnation, the theft of her babies and the endless milking. • 
once the dairy cows are so worn out that they have produced all the milk they can, they are sent to slaughter, usually at around five years of age; the average natural lifespan of a cow is 18 - 22 years. 
their meat often ends up in low-grade burgers or pet foods.
• 
help bring an end to an industry that is violent, unnatural and heart breaking on every level 🙏.
---------------------------------------------------------------

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he’s the only straight man i’ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
“the way the sun is on my skin feels like a million little kisses healing the wounds my body has faced. the way the wind tosses my curls around makes me think that they are dancing and are trying to remind me to dance too. there are so many little things that are beautiful that i forget to notice. the beauty doesn’t end here...” march 22, 2017 
less than a month after i endured the trauma of rape. even with such new wounds, even during the time of reporting to authorities, during the time of wrapping my head around what actually happened to me, i still knew that that wasn’t the end for me. that wasn’t the end of the beauty. this was my actual journal at the time, this was written then in the midst of all the chaos. these are raw real thoughts. sexual assault may feel like it’s the end for you, but it is not there is hope and joy again. 
this is only one of many things that i’ll be sharing on my website that launches on feb 25th, stay tuned friends!!! #metoo #sexualassault #advocate #nottheend

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
happy galentine’s day to three of my kolkata ladies. // soma, who truly takes care of me as my friend, my translator, who holds my hand crossing the busy lanes and prepares delicious meals when our tummies are bothered from “outside food”. aslyn, a soul sister from home who has seen a part of my life that few people have and continues to love and support my best and sometimes grumpy- and-stressed-kolkata-belly self. and maura, who collects craft materials for months, pushes me creatively, shares gin and tonics on rooftops and gets me to dance to bowie in the street. thank you @sarahjsymons1 for being the link that connects us all. xo 
#kolkatadiaries #galentinesday

text:
period shame - 2019
a woman’s world- week 15

last week a new emoji was unveiled that symbolizes periods/menstruation. 
plan international uk’s fight for the red droplet came about to support the fight against periods being embarrassing. 
according to the article stated that 48% of girls and women in the uk aged between 14 and 21 are embarrassed by their periods.

plan uk’s first ever period emoji will be available in march 2019.

text:
#gettoknowclematis ep. 6 - #quellavoltache 
ultimo episodio del recap di ciò che è stato il nostro viaggio finora.
"quella volta che" l'abbiamo girato a fine estate 2018 nel garage del condominio della moli; giorni di pioggia, musica, sperimentazione, lacrime, risate e fotografie. il solito bellissimo casino che accompagna le riprese di tutti i video.
nonostante avessimo già raccontato il problema della violenza sulla donna in altri due video, questa volta volevamo porre l'attenzione sulle vittime e sulle loro emozioni. emozioni che vengono molto spesso giudicate, minimizzate, umiliate e aggredire dalla società. "te la sei cercata", "stronza", "figa di legno".
una vittima di molestie sessuali nel ventunesimo secolo è ancora considerata fastidiosa, esagerata, probabilmente ha frainteso la situazione, poi hai visto com'era vestita. 
e spesso non ce ne accorgiamo nemmeno, perché per la nostra società è normale. 
ma non è normale che sia normale, per citare lo slogan della scorsa giornata internazionale per l'eliminazione della violenza sulle donne. 
allora ricordiamocelo, che noi siamo parte di questa società. e che in quanto tali, per quanto retorico possa sembrare, noi possiamo fare la differenza. possiamo cambiare le cose.
~ @erica_biazzi

ringraziamo ancora una volta l'assessorato alle pari opportunità del comune di cremona e il centro locale parità per averci supportati, capiti e aiutati nella diffusione di questo video.
🌱
#clematis #metoo #comunedicremona #centrolocaleparità #shortfilm #stopviolence #gettoknowus #linkinbio

text:
‘vh1 trailblazer honors’ for ‘the handmaid’s tale’ author & #metoo founder
#
exclusive: vh1 trailblazers honors will celebrate two women closely associated with some timely subjects next month: the handmaid’s tale author margaret atwood and #metoo founder and activist tarana burke. they will be feted as vanguards along with previously announced honorees house speaker nancy pelosi and oscar-nominated filmmaker ava duvernay. the hourlong special will air on vh1 and logo at 9 p.m. friday, march 8 — international women’s day — to mark the kickoff of women’s history month. read vh1‘s mini-bios of burke and atwood below. vh1 rita ora is set to perform her personal anthem “soul survivor,” and additional talent will be announced. vh1 trailblazer honors will celebrate today’s most respected politicians, entertainers, artists, activists, allies and icons who have dedicated their time and steadfast commitments to the women’s movement and beyond,” vh1 said. centered on the past year’s incredible breakthroughs in female empowerment and human rights, the annual event will feature the landmark achievements of its honorees. the event will take place at the wilshire ebell theatre in los angeles, a national historic landmark and extension of the ebell of los angeles, a 125-year-old organization founded by women for women. vh1 trailblazer honors is executive produced by amy doyle, vanessa whitewolf and andria parides, with…

nyc sat 16: looking forward to speaking with some friends sisters comrades this saturday, a day of talks under the umbrella #raperepresentationandradicality the talk i'm in is last of day called "visible invisibility: woc in the context of the #metoo movement"
presenters: maria hupfield (independent artist), viva ruiz (independent artist), scheherazade tillet (a long walk home), jasmine wahi (school of visual arts; project for empty space)  you are invited! check out whole schedule here, it's free.🌻 #repost @projectforemptyspace
• • • • •
🗣 february 16th: join us at this year’s tfap day of panels for caa co chaired by co-director jasmine wahi @browngirlcurator and 2018 fir christen clifford @cd_clifford. this year caa is exploring the dim space that so few people have wanted to discuss for so long- the place where art and rape culture convene and fester. wahi and clifford are ripping the bandaid off and convening some phenomenal radical femmes to wax on empowerment, rape, sex, and art. free & open to the public!  #tfap2019 #raperepresentationradicality #caa2019#badassbrownchick #tfap #curator #rapeculture

text:
black women have always been vulnerable to violence in this country and have long been judged as having no selves to defend. we, at @afrikanmartialarts, reject this judgment and are offering this full day of training to help counter  it.

sunday, february 24: 
in the sisters’ safety & self-defense symposium, you will learn skills to help you prevent, interrupt, heal from, and end violence and abuse. 
in this highly intensive gathering of experts in the fields of security, risk assessment, self-defense, crisis management and conflict resolution, you will learn: •	situational awareness
•	avoiding violence
•	identifying danger signals
•	assertiveness and verbal self-defense
•	the warrior’s mindset
•	escapes from common grabs, holds and chokes
•	basic techniques to get back to your feet after falling or being knocked down
•	improvised weapons 
get on the right side of the barricade and be there!
$45 @door
$40 in advance 
#selfdefense
#blackprepper
#metoo
#neverunarmed
#notavictim

text:
i am honored to be a guest on the @onsovereignwings podcast. amber asked me to share my #metoo story for this beautiful project over a year ago. it's a big, brave thing for me to share this. because it's not a "cut and dry" story of sexual assault, i fear it may be met with criticism and skepticism. but it's a story worth sharing and exploring. i hope you'll be brave and go on the journey with me.

amber and i recorded this episode three different times to make sure we got it just right. it turned out beautifully.  i hope you take some time in the near future to listen, and maybe share with anyone you feel may benefit also.

#metoo #ldswomen #mormonwomen #survivor #healing #podcast

i just wanted to share my thoughts with y'all ❤

#metoo movement is losing the objective by supporting these two proven liars and it's risking the credibility of real victims. this movement has been take over by the opportunists, publicity & money seeker like wade & james to fulfil their person agenda, they are undoubtedly using it to gain attention, fame, & money.

i'm not surprised by seeing tarana burke supporting these two proven liars cause #metoo encouraged people to blindly believe every allegations & the men of sexual assault is presumed guilty until proven innocent when it should be other way around. in this case also they instantly believed two proven liars & mj as a guilty, even tho he was found not guilty on all counts by a court.

i always feel that #metoo has a lack of authenticity cause they don't care about facts & evidence, they don't care that any allegations should be investigated, not blindly believed. they don't care about reputation of innocent man.

this encouraged people like wade & james to defame innocent man under #metoo movement, they are simply throwing wild allegations, unsubstantiated claims and facts against the man who's no longer here to defend himself & no one is questioning them because "believe the victims" so there's no room for debate, these people are immediately supporting two proven liars before checking facts. what's more dangerous & devastating is people are rushing to judgments.

they're ignoring the fbi reports who investigated mj for more than decades and found nothing. they're ignoring how these men changed their stories repeatedly. they're ignoring all the facts & figures. this is extremely destructive for deceased person reputation. no matter if man is innocent but his reputation is destroyed because of these false allegations. #metoo is corrupted by false allegations & opportunism. unfortunately, it will cause harm to actual victims of crime.

text:
justice and forgiveness: 
a conversation on sexual assault
with rachael denhollander

who: stanford community and friends
when: wednesday, february 20th at 7:00 pm
where: paul brest hall (munger residences building 4
559 nathan abbott way, stanford)

rachel denhollander is a lawyer and former gymnast, widely known as the first woman to publicly accuse larry nassar—former team doctor for usa gymnastics and michigan state university—of sexual assault. a 15-year-old club gymnast when nassar first assaulted her, denhollander went on to study law before coming forward with her accusations in 2016. her courage inspired an outflow of witnesses, turning nassar’s case into a nationwide reckoning on power, manipulation, and justice. in 2018, after nassar had been tried and convicted, denhollander then pierced the national conscience with an uncompromising testimony at his sentencing hearing. her speech raised pressing questions for our current cultural moment: what is justice? who is to be believed? where do mercy and forgiveness come in? on february 20, veritas at stanford will be hosting denhollander for an exploration of these ideas. the forum will explore denhollander’s experience as a victim and advocate; the personal and religious forces behind her advocacy; and what all this means for the nation which spawned the global #metoo movement. 
you are welcome to submit questions for the speaker through this form in advance as well as during the forum.

text:
🗣 women unite! reclaim the night! 🗣
next thursday 21st february i will be marching alongside @manchester_su in #manchester’s annual reclaim the night march from #fallowfield to oxford road 📢😮🙌🏼 why would i leave my kids at home on a cold #halfterm night to walk the freezing streets of manchester and shout up for #womensrights?! well because #reclaimthenight is an annual women’s campaign that marches for safety on the streets. and i want my little girl to grow up in a world where she feels safe to walk streets of her home town and not feel threatened by dangerous predators who lurk in the shadows, waiting to pounce on a vulnerable woman who is unprotected by an overworked and underfunded police force.
_
with this campaign i stand with my sisters to ‘reclaim’ the streets at night and demand more provisions to help women feel more safe. because if i add myself to the march today, maybe she will feel safe tomorrow 🖤

text:
today i’m calling you out. i’m calling out very single guy that thinks it’s okay to send inappropriate messages to me or any woman out there. who think it’s okay to comment in a disgusting manner on our appearances. who think it’s okay to be a creep or a douche. ⁣
⁣
today i’m saying no it’s not okay for myself and for any other woman out there, that finds herself being constantly objectified to these remarks. we don’t deserve them and they are wrong on so many levels. ⁣
⁣
up until today i have ignored them, i have called these guys creeps. but ignoring it doesn’t make the problem go away, ignoring it actually sends a message that it is okay. when it’s not okay, it’s not okay on any level. ⁣
⁣
if you think it’s okay then maybe it’s time to give your head a shake. maybe sit in our shoes for a moment. how would you feel if it was your wife, your sister, your cousin, your mom? ⁣
⁣
even better how would you feel if us ladies were sending you those messages. if we were objectifying you? if we were treating you like a piece of meat? i’m guessing you wouldn’t like it all. ⁣
⁣
it doesn’t matter what a woman is wearing in her picture on facebook. it’s not an invitation to comment about her face or her body. ⁣
⁣
today i found my voice and i will keep talking about it. today i’m mad and i’m standing up for what’s right. today i’m speaking for me and any woman out there who has gone through this. i won’t stop speaking up, the time to stop this is right now!

je vais me faire discret ces 2 prochains jours car ce jeudi, le soleil étant avec nous, je pars en vadrouille photos et vendredi je passe un examen médical. un docteur, je l'espère qu'il est docteur, va faire des photos et vidéos de mon moi intérieur, je lui signerais un autographe s'il insiste.
je suis aussi fatigué pour le moment, donc veuillez excuser mes oublis, conversations ennuyeuses, ... pleins de câlins à tous!

text:
doing the work. 
so this quote i share on stage, it's something that a young lady i have mentored for a few years said to me after i asked how she was going with some techniques i had shared with her.

i wanted to slap her and laugh at the same time.

this is a very human response and a typical one, we have so much 'resistance' to doing our work especially inner work.

it's uncomfortable to stir things up.
it's uncomfortable to feel our feelings deeply.
it's uncomfortable to sit still on the meditation mat.

the blocks that come up to do this work are real & scary... there is push back to avoid, check out and numb.

so you stop and start a lil...
you fall down & get back up 
you pay now or pay later.

so choose to do the work. 
the work of fighting against that resistance.
the work of developing yourself. 
the work of sitting on the meditation mat. 
the work of sitting with your feelings.

pick 1 small thing to 'work' on. start slowly and lovingly.

but don't say 'i tried it once and it didn't work'. it will work when you work it.

love you guys xo.

text:
decía ayer maría sotomayor en su cuenta @emedemua : «si las cosas se ponen bravas yo me pongo dura». y claro, yo pienso que en esta vida de esperpento continuo no nos queda otra. pero ayer estuve todo el día arrugada porque violencia administrativa (hija de patriarcado) pasaba por casa. y yo sé decir «fuego» y «volcán» y palabras que queman, y «bengala» y «chiribita» y palabras que brillan, pero me da miedo decir la verdad porque estoy acostumbrada a que mi verdad no cuente una mierda. resulta que adolezco de feminidad asignada: cuando me putean lloro, no pataleo, no lucho, no digo «soy» con los dientes transparentes. debería hacer todo eso en vez de callarme y arrugarme como una flor marchita, lo sé, el problema es que solo después del llanto me acuerdo del enfado. ¿y si escribo, y si hablo y si digo? la violencia hay que nombrarla, amigas. escribiré en voz bien alta «arder» para que no se nos olvide. .
.
.
#escrituracreativa #arder #feminismos #feminism #tribumarcapersonal #nombrarlaviolencia #metoo #escribir #noesno #poesía

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting, wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
day 13 of sexual abuse in the black community:

oprah winfrey “i was raped when i was 9 by a cousin, and never told anybody until i was in my late 20s. not only was i raped by a cousin, i was raped by a cousin, and then later sexually molested by a friend of the family, and then by an uncle,” oprah shared in a 1991 academy of achievement interview.

oprah has aired multiple conversations with survivors of diverse sexual assault experiences. she found that both children and adults were able to come forward and share their painful stories with her. “that is exactly the reason why i wanted to do these shows,” oprah says. “to get people to step out of the shame, to come forward, to tell somebody.” https://www.cheatsheet.com/health-fitness/celebrities-reveal-their-horrifying-experiences-with-sexual-violence-heres-how-theyre-fighting-back.html/

#onetouchtransformation #blackhistorymonth #blackcommunity #sexualabuseawareness #csa #rape #molestation #survivors #metoo #sexualabusesurvivors #sexualabuse #abuse #oprahwinfrey #oprah

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting, wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
ochre ribbon week occurs annually between 12th - 19th february. the ochre ribbon campaign is an initiative supported by the national family violence prevention legal services forum and its member organisations across australia. the ochre ribbon campaign raises awareness of the devastating impacts of family violence in aboriginal and torres strait islander communities and calls for action to end the violence against aboriginal and torres strait islander people – especially our women and children. 
violence against aboriginal and torres strait islander women devastates communities and destroys families. in comparison with other women, aboriginal and torres strait islander women are 32 times more likely to be hospitalised from family violence and 10 times more likely to be killed as a result of violent assault. 
you can raise awareness of this national crisis and show your support for the work of the national forum by sharing these infographics on social media. kan någon snälla köpa mig snart? man går gata upp och gata ner, dröjer länge vid varje bil som saktar in eller parkerar. spanar in i bilar efter män, hoppas få se någon komma körandes ensam utan sällskap i passagerarsätet. det är november och man har på sig en axellös klänning som slutar ovanför knäna och en bomberjacka över. kan någon snälla köpa mig innan jag fryser fast? man står på gatan och spanar efter torskar medan man samtidigt konverserar med ett tiotal torskar över olika appar. ingen man skriver med känns som ett säkert kort eftersom dom velar så mycket och därför kastar man blickar åt alla män som promenerar eller kör på prostitutionssttråket. det man vill mest av allt är att hoppa in i en bil och få pengar. det man vill minst av allt i hela världen är att bli körd någonstans och utsatt för övergreppet torsken vill ha i utbyte. det är kallt, man är abstinent, pengarna är slut och man är desperat och vill ha någonstans att sova. men för att kunna det måste någon köpa en. kan någon snälla bara köpa mig snart? det är allt man har i huvudet när man går där på gatan och är så desperat efter pengar, sömn och knark. hela kroppen skriker, man vill köpa mat och bädda ner sig och komma in i värmen men först måste någon köpa en. så även om det sista man vill är att ”ha sex” med en främmande man i hans bil eller utomhus så är det också det enda som står emellan en själv och alla behov som man akut har. #prostitution #metoo #intedinhora

text:
breakfree from shame.
the only way to change how we deal with sexual assault is to change how we deal with shame. it's time to transfer shame from the victim to the perpetrator and their enablers.

shame, by the way, is why #metoo is being used by all kinds of victims of sexual assault. the shame of having been raped is so great that it's only in standing in solidarity with women who've been subject to a different form of sexual violence that many rape victims feel comfortable admitting anything happened to them at all.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
instagram: i’m so happy, i’m making so much progress everyday and taking care of myself and working out everyday. i’ve overcome a lot and now life is perfect.⠀
⠀
reality: i’m struggling, with body image, with my mindset and with confusing bloat for weight gain. yes that’s a real struggle and when you have stomach issues all the time you’re pretty much constantly bloated.⠀
⠀
just here to shed some light that life isn’t always how it looks on instagram. people show you the highlight reel, the good stuff. why? because it’s so so hard to be vulnerable and share the not so great stuff, to share that we struggle too.⠀
⠀
this is what we connect with though. we connect with people who can say ‘me too’ to the hard things we’ve been through or are going through. we connect we those we relate too and we help others know they aren’t alone. heck we let ourselves know we aren’t alone.⠀
⠀
i promise you’re not the only one going through what you’re going through, you’re never alone. i encourage you to be vulnerable today. share something you’re struggling with today with a friend, family member, or with me if you feel comfortable, i’m always here girl because no one should ever feel alone 💓

.

text:
within 7 days of each other my sister @paulalwhite literally had the last word in a new york times 📰📰 article on education and i was on the today show 🎤📺talking about young men and #metoo (link in bio). how’s that for sisters getting it done?!! 💃🏾💃🏾🥂🥂she is a list-maker 📝 and box-checker and she got to check that box on her list of career goals. i’m the one who puts things on a list after i’ve done them, though i gotta admit that being an ‘expert’ on tv was one of those “wouldn’t it be cool if that happened?” moments that sometimes crossed my mind. 
we didn’t get to 🎉🎉 our achievements in person. but this celebratory pic was taken on my last trip to see her - which was a very last minute mileage run on new year’s eve - and we had a one-day-early 🎂🎂 dinner for me. 
i am always the one ✈️ to see her on the other coast due to my location-independent job that allows me to travel on a whim. but this year she has to spend a $2000 travel voucher she got from united for getting bumped (i’m hater level jealous 🤑), and so she will soon be coming to see me on the west coast for the first time in at least a decade. 
where are you traveling to see your sister this year? tag them and let us know where you’re going.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

#taranaburke's career has been spent uniting us; #metoo allowed 19 million people across 85 countries to declare that we've been affected by sexual violence. @girlsforgenderequity, the non-profit she founded, creates opportunities for young women and girls to live self-determined lives by tackling the many obstacles young women and girls face such as sexism, racial inequality, homophobia, transphobia, and sexual harassment. her most recent work with the #muterkelly movement has allowed the rest of the world to connect to the scores of black women who have, until now, had to stand in silence as the violence, manipulation and abuse they suffered went ignored, and r kelly's wealth built. her involvement in the project has opened us to the prevalence of sexual violence, to its insidiousness, and to our ability to heal each other when we choose to #believewomen. 
for teaching us how to listen and for her work ending the suffering in silence, this #blackhistorymonth we honor @taranajaneen
.

text: so incredibly stoked for this amazing birthday present today, a little feature in @vogueliving feb / march issue is out today, on the era of #metoo and shining a light on women. “i want my images to move viewers to consider how we respond to the female body and to the environment. we’re living in a time where the frustration and anger about the inequality of of women’s rights in society and the destruction of the earth are bubbling to the surface. it’s the conundrum of how to represent one’s individual beauty and the beauty within oneself without being constantly sexualised. i photograph women in a bid to understand my own femaleness.” thank you so much to @freyaherring for the beautiful article 💕💕

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
"lo más triste que puede hacer una mujer, es hacerse la tonta sólo para gustarle a un hombre"
-emma watson 
antes de compartir lo siguiente quiero aclarar que actualmente soy soltera. no tengo un esposo golpeador, ni un novio maltratador. mencionó esto para que ninguna de mis amigas o familia se preocupen. simplemente me inspiró hacer con maquillaje, una expresión sobre este tema, en lo personal siempre he apoyado e incitado a la lucha contra la violencia hacia la mujer. 
pienso que es muy curioso qué los hombres tomen la lucha de nosotras las mujeres contra la violencia de género como una guerra personal. si tú nunca has golpeado u ofendido a una mujer, porque te incómodas? porque te molesta? precisamente, si no eres así, deberías de apoyar este movimiento que hace quedar tan mal a tu género. la mujer nació para ser respetada y admirada en la misma media que un hombre. 
#niunamenos #niunamas #metoo #stopviolence

text:
lisa flotlin, 29, was sexually assaulted by her high school spanish teacher when she was 17. eight years later, at 25, she realized she wanted to press charges but, due to convoluted statute of limitations laws, found out that she no longer had the option to seek justice. she is now sharing her story to help prompt changes to statute of limitations laws, including simplifying and extending the reporting period.
#metoo #seattle #waleg

text:
black women have always been vulnerable to violence in this country and have long been judged as having no selves to defend. @afrikanmartialarts rejects this judgment and is offering this full day of training to help counter it.

the sisters’ safety & self-defense symposium is designed for women of african descent, ages 11-adult, from martial arts experts, to combat veterans, to women with zero martial arts experience.

in this highly intensive gathering of experts in the fields of security, risk assessment, self-defense, crisis management and conflict resolution, you will learn: •	situational awareness
•	avoiding violence
•	identifying danger signals
•	assertiveness and verbal self-defense
•	the warrior’s mindset
•	escapes from common grabs, holds and chokes
•	basic techniques to get back to your feet after falling or being knocked down
•	improvised weapons

just $45.00 for the entire day at the door.
$40.00 advance (send to cashapp: $balogunojetade). #notavictim
#neverunarmed
#blackprepper

text:
at a young age, our culture teaches girls "dress this way otherwise men won't respect you. act this way otherwise men won't respect you.." let me tell you something if a boy is raised right, he will become a man who learns to respect everyone at all times. women are not binary. we are humans with real emotions and feelings. "oh but what if she doesn't respect herself??" so what?! because someone doesn't respect themselves doesnt give anyone an excuse to treat someone lower than themselves. be kind to them. and honestly the person you think you doesnt respect themselves probably loves and respects themselves more than the person who would ask that as a response. respect is not about superficial appearances. respect is about your attitude. respect is about honoring people who are different than you. respect is about boundaries. women are disrespected left and right for all kinds of reasons and then we are the ones left to feel like trash. we are the ones left to question "what did i do wrong to be made to feel this way?" when the reality should be "wow that person is super shitty." and god forbid if we bring it up and get told "well maybe if you didnt do that.. that wouldn't have happened." the shame for bringing up mistreatment. the judgment for someone else's actions. there is no accountability for the action of disrespect. 
and dont get me wrong i understand respect is a two way street.. men should be respected as well. i am speaking for women because as a woman it is easier for me to speak from experience but i do also speak for the men that remain silent. it is not right. respect is not binary. you either have it or you don't. there are no stipulations "i'll respect you if you act this way." that isnt respect. that is favor. respect says "i'll treat you like a human regardless of how you look, dress, what you believe." favor says "i'll treat you like a human you as long as you fit my criteria." .
.

text_retweet:
#repost @makerswomen
・・・
“anything less than a woman being enthusiastic about something sexual that is about to happen is a sign that he must stop and talk to her.” - @jameelajamilofficial got real about talking to boys about sex and consent 🙌#makersconference ・・・
here's what i have to say👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼
this post came up on my feed last week, and it made me really happy. happy because it highlights #metoo as a movement towards positive change, rather than an expression of anger. i say this as someone with more than enough to be angry about; if that's what i wanted. being angry is a phase - let it out or let it go - but anger alone doesn't lead to a solution. jameela's proposition, on the other hand, is full of common sense (when pre-conceived notions are put aside). it's a bright expression of the beautiful, open-minded side of society that exists today; the world where gender is non-binary and sex for pleasure is celebrated!

i want more of this!

spread the love everyday! ❤️🧡💛💚💙💜
